Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
ARCADIS U.S., Inc. (ARCADIS) was retained by the New Orleans Regional Transit
Authority (RTA) to perform traffic analyses as part of the Cemeteries Transit Center
Environmental Assessment project. The purpose of this project is to improve safety
for transit riders by consolidating bus-to-streetcar passenger transfers in a safe
location. The project is located near the Interstate 10 (I-10) at Metairie Road
interchange in the city of New Orleans, Louisiana, within Orleans Parish, as shown
The project proposes to move the existing Canal Streetcar Cemeteries stop at the
intersection of Canal Street and City Park Avenue to the Cemeteries Transit Center
at Canal Boulevard north of City Park Avenue in order to consolidate bus and
In response to comments from federal, state, and local agencies and the public, the
original 30 percent design was revised to avoid impacting the Canal Boulevard
median. The current project design allows the streetcar to operate in the left travel
lanes of Canal Boulevard, terminating at the first turnbay north of City Park Avenue.
Bus lines will utilize existing stops in the other two turnbays and along Canal
Boulevard. This report summarizes the traffic operational analysis for these revised
conditions as shown in the 60 percent design plans.
Intersection and arterial capacity analyses were performed for existing, no build, and
build scenarios. Analysis of build conditions include open year (2015) and design
year (2035) analysis. Morning (AM) and evening (PM) peak hours were analyzed for
The Study Area for the traffic analysis consists of the following segments:
City Park Avenue between I-10 eastbound and Bienville Avenue;
Canal Street between North Bernadotte Street and City Park Avenue; and
Canal Boulevard between City Park Avenue and Weiblen Road.

Currently, City Park Avenue is a two-way, four-lane divided urban minor arterial road
with four signalized and two primary unsignalized intersections in the Study Area.
Canal Street is a two-way, five-lane divided urban principal arterial road
signalized and two primary unsignalized intersections in the Study Area. Canal
Boulevard is a two-way, four-lane urban principal arterial road
unsignalized intersections in the Study Area. The signalized and unsignalized
intersections analyzed are listed in Table 1. The posted speed limits on City Park
Avenue, Canal Street, and Canal Boulevard are 35 miles per hour in the Study Area.
The project location is surrounded by cemeteries; therefore, geometric improvements
that can be performed at the proposed project location are very limited.

assess and characterize the recent crash history in the Study Area. Segment crash
rates, fatality rates, injury rates, and crash frequencies by collision type were
developed for the Study Area. Crash data for 3 years (2007 through 2009) were
obtained from the New Orleans Regional Planning Commission (RPC) for Jefferson,
Orleans, Plaquemines, St. Bernard, and St. Tammany Parishes to develop these
LADOTD Highway Functional Systems based on 2000 Census.

Tables 2 and 3 summarize the crash analysis results in the Study Area for years
2007 through 2009. On average, 82 crashes and 27 non-fatal injuries were
experienced in the Study Area each year. No fatalities were experienced.

page.text: ARCADIS collected turning movement counts and 48-hour vehicle classification
counts in the Study Area. The counts were collected from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m. and from
4 p.m. to 6 p.m. on a Tuesday and Wednesday in November 2011. The location of
the tube counters is shown on Figure 2. Before the interstate and arterial traffic
growth rates were applied, monthly and daily adjustment factors were applied to
convert the turning counts to a normalized vehicle volume. The adjustment factors
applied were calculated and provided by the Louisiana Department of Transportation
and Development (LADOTD). The Study Area contains a collection of both major
and minor urban arterials, interstate ramps, and urban collector and local roads.
Table 5 shows the adjustment factors used.
Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
The K-Factor for this project was calculated by taking the ratio of the peak hour
volumes to the daily volumes collected in the field via 48-hour tube counts. A
weighted average by total volume at tube count locations was taken, and K-Factors
of 8.1 percent for surface streets and 6.8 percent for I-10 were determined. Truck
percentages were also determined from the vehicle classification data. As shown in
Table 6, a 24-hour average truck percentage of 5.6 percent was determined for
surface streets, with 4.8 percent for single units and 0.8 percent for combination
units. The truck percentage on I-10 was 10.1 percent, with 7.5 percent for single
units and 2.6 percent for combination units. In addition, when examining the peak
traffic periods, a truck percentage of 4.4 percent was determined on surface streets,
with 3.5 percent for single units and 0.9 percent for combined units. The truck
percentage on I-10 during the peak traffic periods was 8.2 percent, with 5.4 percent
for single units and 2.8 percent for combined units.
LADOTD’s daily and seasonal factors were also applied to the 2009 intersection
peak-hour turning movement counts to estimate peak-hour volumes for an average
day. The daily and seasonal factors were obtained from the Office of Planning and
Programming of LADOTD in October 2009 and are included in Appendix B. The
adjusted intersection counts were balanced to generate existing (2011) design hourly
volumes (DHVs) and were converted to average daily traffic (ADT) volumes based on
the K-Factor obtained from traffic counts provided in Appendix C.
Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
LADOTD’s daily and seasonal factors were used to adjust the 24-hour count data to
ADT level. The adjusted ADT volumes, obtained from peak-hour turning volumes,
were used to verify the roadway segment.
Peak hour turning movement counts were rounded to the nearest five vehicles, and
ADT volumes were rounded to the nearest ten vehicles. The existing ADT volumes
and DHVs are provided in Appendix D.
The project is planned for open year 2015 and design year 2035. Traffic projections
were performed for the open year (2015) and the design year (2035) for the no build
and build scenario. Growth trends were calculated using historical ADT volumes
from LADOTD and the RPC travel demand model volumes.
Historical volumes taken from one LADOTD count station on Metairie Road and
three count stations on I-10 in the Study Area (shown on Figure 2 and listed in
Table 7) were used in growth trend calculation. Historical annual ADTs from 1973
through 2010 suggest that the project corridors (Canal Street, Canal Boulevard and
City Park Avenue within the study area) has grown at a consistent rate of
0.88 percent. On the other hand, the counters on I-10 showed an average growth

page.text: Growth trends from RPC’s travel demand model were also analyzed. Daily volumes
were obtained from the model for years 2012 and 2033. Analysis showed the yearly

The RPC Metropolitan Transportation Plan Fiscal Year (FY) 2011 to 2040 and
Transportation Improvement Program FY 2011 to 2014 and FY 2013 to 2016 were
reviewed to identify projects programmed to be built between 2011 and 2035 that
would impact the traffic volumes in the Study Area. It is concluded that none of the
programmed projects would have an impact.
Traffic impact studies for related future development projects within and around the
Study Area were reviewed. Based on discussions with RPC and further research, it
was concluded that the traffic volumes in the Study Area would not be impacted by
any proposed developments in the region.
Based on observations described above, average growth rates of 1.5 percent on
arterials and 0.5 percent on I-10 were used to determine the open year (2015) and
design year (2035) volumes within the project limits.
Traffic projections developed for future year (open and design year) conditions were
used in the analysis of both no build and build conditions. Open year and design
year ADT volumes and DHVs for build conditions are provided in Appendix D.

text.b: 4. Capacity Analysis for No Build and Existing Conditions

page.text: Capacity analysis is the most commonly accepted method for evaluating the quality
of service of highway and street facilities. Level of service (LOS) is a quality
measure that describes operational conditions of these facilities. The Highway
Capacity Manual (HCM) published by the Transportation Research Board outlines
capacity analysis procedures and the criteria for defining LOS.

text.b: Intersection Analysis for No Build and Existing Conditions

page.text: HCM defines six LOS, designated by the letters A through F. LOS A represents the
best operating conditions, and LOS F represents the worst operating conditions.
LOS criteria for signalized and unsignalized intersections are listed in Tables 8 and 9,
Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
Capacity analyses were performed for AM and PM peak hours for existing conditions
and open year and design year no build conditions. Synchro 7’s HCM module was
used for the capacity analyses for all intersections except the intersection of Canal
Boulevard northbound and City Park Avenue westbound. Due to the atypical control,
this intersection was analyzed using HCS+. VISSIM was used for the analyses of
segment operations. The results of the capacity analyses are presented in
Intersection capacity analysis was performed for AM and PM peak hours for existing
conditions and for open year and design year no build conditions. Lane and
intersection configurations for the existing, no build open, and no build design year
scenarios are illustrated on Figure 3. The capacity analysis for the existing year was
performed using the currently implemented signal timings, obtained from the RPC.
Traffic signals on City Park Avenue are actuated and uncoordinated, with I-10
eastbound and westbound ramp intersections being clustered. Signal timings were
optimized for the future year analysis.

Results for the signalized and unsignalized intersections are summarized in
Table 10. The intersection of the I-10 eastbound ramp and City Park Avenue
operates at LOS F in the AM peak period and LOS C in the PM peak period in the
existing year. This is primarily due to high delays for vehicles on the Metairie Road
eastbound approach destined for I-10 eastbound. The average queue for such
vehicles is 620 feet. Design year no build analysis reveals that, as volume
increases, signalized intersections will start operating at LOS F. It is estimated that
three of the four signalized intersections will operate at LOS F.
Table 10 shows the critical approach delays and LOS for unsignalized intersections in
the Study Area. The southbound approach at the City Park Avenue/Canal Boulevard
southbound intersection operates at LOS F during both AM and PM peak hours in the
existing year. This is predominantly due to the heavy southbound volumes having to
yield to the eastbound and westbound traffic. The westbound approach at the City
Park Avenue/Canal Boulevard northbound intersection operates at LOS F during the
The eastbound approach at the intersection of North Bernadotte Street and Canal
Street operates at LOS F in the AM peak period primarily due to left-turning vehicles
having difficulty finding a gap in order to make a turn.
Similarly, the eastbound approach at the intersection of Canal Boulevard northbound
and Rosedale Road operates at LOS F in the PM peak period due to the difficulty of
eastbound vehicles finding a gap in order to make a through movement.
In the design year, all signalized intersections except the City Park Avenue/Bienville
Avenue intersection operate at LOS F due to higher volumes compared to the existing
year. The unsignalized intersections operate at LOS F in at least one of the peak periods.

City Park Avenue eastbound making a left turn onto Canal Boulevard northbound

text.b: Arterial Analysis for No Build and Existing Conditions

page.text: The HCM intersection analysis employs a macro-level estimation methodology that
does not account for the influence of congested segments on the operations of the
intersection. To account for such an influence, a micro-simulation analysis, which
includes a holistic quantification of operations on study segments, was conducted.
VISSIM software was used to conduct the micro-simulation analysis. Similar to the
SYNCHRO analysis, field data including volume, speed, laneage, and intersection
control was used to develop the analysis model. Subsequent to the development of a
base analysis model, volume calibration was performed to ensure that the micro-
simulation analysis reasonably reflects field observed conditions.
Model calibration is the adjustment of model parameters to improve the model’s ability
to reproduce local traffic conditions in order to reasonably predict traffic performance
for the proposed project. Volume calibration of the proposed project VISSIM model
included evaluation of link traffic volumes to ensure that volumes at key bottleneck
areas in the VISSIM models are within an acceptable target range of field traffic counts.
Based on guidelines provided by the Federal Highway Administration, Office of
Operation, Section 5, the acceptable target range for individual link flows for volumes of
less than 2,700 vehicle per hour is 85 percent of the field counts.
For the proposed project, the upstream links at the intersections of City Park Avenue
and Canal Street and Canal Boulevard were selected as the key bottlenecks for model
calibration. The calibrated region for the VISSIM model is highlighted on Figure 6.
It was observed through the model runs and link evaluation that the upstream link
volumes at the key bottleneck areas are either higher or in very close proximity to
85 percent of the field counts. Therefore, it was concluded that the existing AM and
PM VISSIM models are volume-calibrated to be used for future year analysis. Figure 6
also shows the percentage of upstream link volumes to the field counts for comparison.

Based on the 60 percent design, the build conditions included changes to design and
signalization at the intersections of City Park Avenue with Canal Street and with Canal
Boulevard as shown on Figure 9. The remaining roadway segments and study
intersections remain unchanged from the existing condition and are the same for both
build and no build conditions. The lane and intersection configurations for the build
open and design year scenarios are based on the 60 percent design for the project.
Proposed build conditions include new signals at the intersection of Canal Boulevard
and City Park Avenue along with new signals at the median U-turn along Canal
Boulevard north of City Park Avenue. The new signals would function under the
existing signal control at the intersection of Canal Street and City Park Avenue.
The signal phasing that was modeled for build conditions was obtained from RTA
based upon the 60 percent design. However, several comments on the signal phasing
shown in the 60 percent design plan were received from the Department of Public
Works (DPW) on October 24, 2014. As a result, the signal phasing scheme suggested
by DPW was modeled for all analyses in lieu of the ones shown in the 60 percent
design plans. Both of these design schemes are shown on Figure 10.

worsening delays for the build condition in the open year (2015) and the build

Figures 11 and 12 compare modeled delays for buses and streetcars in the no build
and build conditions in 2015 and 2035. In the design year, both buses and streetcars
would be able to make a left turn from City Park Avenue eastbound onto Canal
Boulevard northbound. The streetcar line would function with delay times of 39 and
43 seconds during the AM and PM peak hour for 2035 conditions. Streetcars would be
able to navigate across City Park Avenue with short delays and would not experience
significant delays from queue spillbacks at the Study Area intersections. However,
other movements through the study intersections will experience higher delays and
longer travel times as compared to the no build conditions. This is primarily due to the
implementation of new signals and the operation of these new signals as a single
cluster with the existing signal controller.

and design year build conditions. Table 15 summarizes and Figures 13 and 14

Except for Canal Boulevard southbound and City Park Avenue eastbound (during AM
peak hour) movements, all arterials in the build condition would operate at lower
speeds than the no build condition arterial speeds. The degradation of operations for
build conditions is primarily due to inclusion of the new signals which have to work as a
single cluster with the existing signals. This in turn results in increased cycle length and
the increased number of phases for the build condition as compared to no build
conditions. In addition, the presence of closely spaced signalized intersections results
in slower operating speeds on the segments resulting in higher delays under build
conditions. As discussed before, a macro-level analysis of just the intersection analysis
does not account for the slower segment speeds and queue spillbacks and so the
results of the segment analysis, which provide a better picture of the traffic operations,
were used to develop the conclusions for this study.
As discussed previously, the build condition based on the 60 percent design was
modeled and analyzed for improving transit and traffic operations as well as safety in
the Study Area. Signalizing the Canal Boulevard intersection would improve the transit
rider safety by controlling vehicles on City Park Avenue eastbound as well as
pedestrians crossing City Park Avenue and Canal Boulevard. However, the proposed
new signals also result in increased delays for vehicles traveling on the Study Area
The intersection capacity analysis revealed that traffic improvements on City Park
Avenue would ensure minimization of travel delays for streetcars crossing City Park
Avenue; however, the improvements would bring higher delays for vehicular traffic at
the intersections. The ripple effects of the project at the nearby intersections would not
be significant except for the backups on Canal Street northbound causing higher
delays at the Canal Street/North Anthony Street intersection. Additional optimization of
signal timing along with the optimization of turn-lane configurations at the intersections
hold some promise of further reduction in delays for the build scenario. However, since
the intersection capacity analysis was conducted using methodologies that do not
account for upstream and downstream bottlenecks or the resultant queue spillbacks,
micro-simulation analysis was conducted. Microsimulation analysis accounts for both,
intersection operations and segment queues which provides a better picture of
operations for the study segments and intersections.
Cemeteries Transit Center Environmental Assessment and Section 4(f) Statement
The arterial capacity analysis showed that, similar to intersection operations analysis,
the project would reduce travel speeds on most approaches of the Canal Street and
Canal Boulevard intersections with City Park Avenue.
The safety analysis revealed that, during the 3-year data collection period, angle
collisions, the most frequent type of collision in the Study Area, were predominantly
“left-angle” type incidents. When compared with statewide average crash rates, it was
found that the crash and injury rates on City Park Avenue between I-10 eastbound and
Canal Boulevard Avenue were consistently higher than statewide average crash rates.
In addition, crash and injury rates on City Park Avenue, Canal Boulevard, and Bienville
Street were found to be higher than the statewide average rates in several of the years
The following recommendation was developed based on the results of the analysis for
Signalize and cluster the City Park Avenue/Canal Boulevard intersection with the
City Park Avenue/Canal Street intersection using a single controller.
